I74Iran Sanctions

I21Pub. L. 104ÿ09172, Aug. 5, 1996, 110 Stat. 1541, as amended by Pub. L. 107ÿ0924, ÿ1A2(a), 3ÿ095, Aug. 3, 2001, 115 Stat. 199, 200; Pub. L. 109ÿ09267, ÿ1A1, Aug. 4, 2006, 120 Stat. 680; Pub. L. 109ÿ09293, title II, ÿ1A201ÿ09202(b), 203ÿ09205(g)(1), Sept. 30, 2006, 120 Stat. 1345ÿ091347; Pub. L. 111ÿ09195, title I, ÿ1A102(a)ÿ09(g), July 1, 2010, 124 Stat. 1317ÿ091324; Pub. L. 112ÿ09158, title II, ÿ1A201, 202(a), 203, 204(a), 205ÿ09207(a), title III, ÿ1A311(a), (b)(1), Aug. 10, 2012, 126 Stat. 1219, 1221, 1223, 1225ÿ091227, 1247, 1248, provided that:

S5804

I67T1``SECTION 1. SHORT TITLE.

S5800

I21``This Act may be cited as the `Iran Sanctions Act of 1996'.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 2. FINDINGS.

S5800

I21``The Congress makes the following findings:

I22``(1) The efforts of the Government of Iran to acquire weapons of mass destruction and the means to deliver them and its support of acts of international terrorism endanger the national security and foreign policy interests of the United States and those countries with which the United States shares common strategic and foreign policy objectives.

I22``(2) The objective of preventing the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and acts of international terrorism through existing multilateral and bilateral initiatives requires additional efforts to deny Iran the financial means to sustain its nuclear, chemical, biological, and missile weapons programs.

I22``(3) The Government of Iran uses its diplomatic facilities and quasi-governmental institutions outside of Iran to promote acts of international terrorism and assist its nuclear, chemical, biological, and missile weapons programs.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 3. DECLARATION OF POLICY.

S5800

I21``The Congress declares that it is the policy of the United States to deny Iran the ability to support acts of international terrorism and to fund the development and acquisition of weapons of mass destruction and the means to deliver them by limiting the development of Iran's ability to explore for, extract, refine, or transport by pipeline petroleum resources of Iran.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 4. MULTILATERAL REGIME.

S5800

I21``(a) T4Multilateral NegotiationsK._In order to further the objectives of section 3, the Congress urges the President to commence immediately diplomatic efforts, both in appropriate international fora such as the United Nations, and bilaterally with allies of the United States, to establish a multilateral sanctions regime against Iran, including provisions limiting the development of petroleum resources, that will inhibit Iran's efforts to carry out activities described in section 2.

I21``(b) T4Reports to CongressK._The President shall report to the appropriate congressional committees, not later than 1 year after the date of the enactment of this Act [Aug. 5, 1996], and periodically thereafter, on the extent that diplomatic efforts described in subsection (a) have been successful. Each report shall include_

I22``(1) the countries that have agreed to undertake measures to further the objectives of section 3 with respect to Iran, and a description of those measures; and

I22``(2) the countries that have not agreed to measures described in paragraph (1), and, with respect to those countries, other measures the President recommends that the United States take to further the objectives of section 3 with respect to Iran.

I21``(c) T4Waiver._

I22``(1) T4In generalK._

I23``(A) T4General waiverK._The President may, on a case by case basis, waive for a period of not more than six months the application of section 5(a) with respect to a national of a country, if the President certifies to the appropriate congressional committees at least 30 days before such waiver is to take effect that such waiver is vital to the national security interests of the United States.

I23``(B) T4Waiver with respect to persons in countries that cooperate in multilateral efforts with respect to iranK._The President may, on a case by case basis, waive for a period of not more than 12 months the application of section 5(a) with respect to a person if the President, at least 30 days before the waiver is to take effect_

I24``(i) certifies to the appropriate congressional committees that_

I36``(I) the government with primary jurisdiction over the person is closely cooperating with the United States in multilateral efforts to prevent Iran from_

S5804

I24``(aa) acquiring or developing chemical, biological, or nuclear weapons or related technologies; or

I24``(bb) acquiring or developing destabilizing numbers and types of advanced conventional weapons; and

S5800

I36``(II) such a waiver is vital to the national security interests of the United States; and

I24``(ii) submits to the appropriate congressional committees a report identifying_

I36``(I) the person with respect to which the President waives the application of sanctions; and

I36``(II) the actions taken by the government described in clause (i)(I) to cooperate in multilateral efforts described in that clause.

I22``(2) T4Subsequent renewal of waiverK._At the conclusion of the period of a waiver under subparagraph (A) or (B) of paragraph (1), the President may renew the waiver_

I23``(A) if the President determines, in accordance with subparagraph (A) or (B) of that paragraph (as the case may be), that the waiver is appropriate; and

I23``(B)(i) in the case of a waiver under subparagraph (A) of paragraph (1), for subsequent periods of not more than six months each; and

I24``(ii) in the case of a waiver under subparagraph (B) of paragraph (1), for subsequent periods of not more than 12 months each.

I21``(d) T4Interim Report on Multilateral Sanctions; MonitoringK._The President, not later than 90 days after the date of the enactment of this Act, shall report to the appropriate congressional committees on_

I22``(1) whether the member states of the European Union, the Republic of Korea, Australia, Israel, or Japan have legislative or administrative standards providing for the imposition of trade sanctions on persons or their affiliates doing business or having investments in Iran or Libya;

I22``(2) the extent and duration of each instance of the application of such sanctions; and

I22``(3) the disposition of any decision with respect to such sanctions by the World Trade Organization or its predecessor organization.

I21``(e) T4Investigations._

I22``(1) T4In generalK._The President shall initiate an investigation into the possible imposition of sanctions under section 5(a) against a person upon receipt by the United States of credible information indicating that such person is engaged in an activity described in such section.

I22``(2) T4Determination and notificationK._Not later than 180 days after an investigation is initiated in accordance with paragraph (1), the President shall (unless paragraph (3) applies) determine, pursuant to section 5(a), if a person has engaged in an activity described in such section and shall notify the appropriate congressional committees of the basis for any such determination.

I22``(3) T4Special ruleK._The President need not initiate an investigation, and may terminate an investigation, under this subsection if the President certifies in writing to the appropriate congressional committees that_

I23``(A) the person whose activity was the basis for the investigation is no longer engaging in the activity or has taken significant verifiable steps toward stopping the activity; and

I23``(B) the President has received reliable assurances that the person will not knowingly engage in an activity described in section 5(a) in the future.

I21``(f) T4Briefings on ImplementationK._Not later than 90 days after the date of the enactment of the Iran Threat Reduction and Syria Human Rights Act of 2012 [Aug. 10, 2012], and every 120 days thereafter, the President, acting through the Secretary of State, shall provide to the appropriate congressional committees a comprehensive briefing on efforts to implement this Act.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 5. IMPOSITION OF SANCTIONS.

S5800

I21``(a) T4Sanctions Relating to the Energy Sector of Iran._

I22``(1) T4Development of petroleum resources of iran._

I23``(A) T4In generalK._Except as provided in subsection (f), the President shall impose 5 or more of the sanctions described in section 6(a) with respect to a person if the President determines that the person knowingly, on or after the date of the enactment of the Iran Threat Reduction and Syria Human Rights Act of 2012 [Aug. 10, 2012]_

I24``(i) makes an investment described in subparagraph (B) of $20,000,000 or more; or

