I74National Commission on Defense and National Security

I21Pub. L. 101ÿ09511, title VIII, ÿ1A8104, Nov. 5, 1990, 104 Stat. 1898, as amended by Pub. L. 102ÿ09172, title VIII, ÿ1A8078, Nov. 26, 1991, 105 Stat. 1189, provided that:

I21``SECTION 1. This section establishes the National Commission on Defense and National Security.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 2. FINDINGS.

S5800

I21``The Congress makes the following findings:

I22``(1) Recent revolutionary world events require a fundamental reassessment of the defense and national security policies of the United States.

I22``(2) Emerging democracies around the world will require political, technical, and economic assistance, as well as military assistance, from the developed free nations in order to thrive and to become productive members of the world community.

I22``(3) Real and potential military threats to the United States and its allies will continue to exist for the foreseeable future from not just the Soviet Union but also from terrorism and from Third World nations.

I22``(4) Proliferation of both sophisticated conventional weapons and of nuclear weapons could produce a world more dangerous than we have faced in the past.

I22``(5) Ethnic rivalries as well as economic inequalities may produce instabilities that could spark serious conflict.

I22``(6) In order to formulate coherent national policies to meet these challenges of a new world environment, it is essential for the United States to achieve a bipartisan consensus such as that which emerged following World War II.

I22``(7) Such a consensus can be fostered by the development of policy recommendations from a highly respected group of individuals who do not bear a partisan label and who possess critical expertise and experience.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 3. ESTABLISHMENT.

S5800

I21``There is established a commission to be known as [the] National Commission on Defense and National Security (hereinafter in this Act referred to as the `Commission'). The Commission is established until 30 days following submission of the final report required by section 6 of this section.

S5804

I67T1``SEC. 4. DUTIES OF COMMISSION.

S5800

I21``(a) T4In GeneralK._The Commission shall analyze and make recommendations to the President and Congress concerning the national security and national defense policies of the United States.

I21``(b) T4Matters To Be AnalyzedK._Matters to be analyzed by the Commission shall include the following:

I22``(1) The world-wide interests, goals, and objectives of the United States that are vital to the national security of the United States.

I22``(2) The political, economic, and military developments around the world and the implications of those developments for United States national security interests, including_

I23``(A) the developments in Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union;

I23``(B) the question of German unification;

I23``(C) the future of NATO and European economic integration;

I23``(D) the future of the Pacific Basin; and

I23``(E) potential instability resulting from regional conflicts or economic problems in the developing world.

I22``(3) The foreign policy, world-wide commitments, and national defense capabilities of the United States necessary to deter aggression and implement the national security strategy of the United States, including the contribution that can be made by bilateral and multilateral political and economic associations in promoting interests that the United States shares with other members of the world community.

I22``(4) The proposed short-term uses of the political, economic, military, and other elements of national power for the United States to protect or promote the interests and to achieve the goals and objectives referred to in paragraph (1).

